<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-559-679  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 559 679.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Oct 30 1990 v4 n37 p6(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Illustrator 3.0 charts new course. (Adobe Systems Inc.'s AdobeIllustrator 3.0 computer graphics software) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Said, Carolyn.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Adobe Systems Inc introduces Adobe Illustrator 3.0, an improvedand more accessible version of its graphics software.andP;  Illustrator3.0 is available for $595 to new users and costs $99 for theupgrade.andP;  In 1991 the upgrade cost rises to $149.andP;  Illustrator'stext handling is improved and the interface has been streamlinedto make the product easier to use.andP;  Built-in charting features anda new higher character limit are welcome changes.andP;  AdobeIllustrator 3.0 can change fonts to editable outlines and providesexcellent text manipulation, according to users.andP;  Adobe Separatorand Adobe Type Manager 2.0 are bundled with Illustrator 3.0.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Adobe Systems Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Ticker:    ADBE.andO;Product:   Illustrator 3.0 (Computer graphics software) (Productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionComputer GraphicsGraphics Software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Designers pleased with new  featuresandM;By Carolyn SaidandM;Mountain View, Calif.andP;  -- Graphic designers responded with enthusiasm to lastweek's release of Adobe Illustrator Version 3.0, but not without suggestionsfor subsequent upgrades to Adobe Systems Inc.'s widely used PostScriptillustration program.andM;Improved text handling, built-in charting capabilities and a simplifiedinterface designed to make the program more accessible highlight the newversion, which carries a price tag of $595.andM;andgt;Text handling.andP;  Users said they were pleased that Adobe had deleted theprogram's anemic 256-character limit and clumsy text-dialog box.andP;  &quot;The textmanipulation is fantastic,&quot; said Raquel Aceves, manager and project directorat Graphic Advantage in Encinitas, Calif.andP;  Aceves said she particularly likedthe program's new ability to convert fonts into editable outlines, but wouldlike to see special characters such as small caps and superscripts added.andO;Tabulation also would be helpful, said Karl Hartig, a graphic designer forthe Wall Street Journal in New York.andP;  &quot;We could be doing tables orchart-table combinations if tabs were included,&quot; he said.andM;andgt;Charting.andP;  Brand-new charting features let users create bar, line, area,scanner and pie charts that are automatically updated when data changes.andO;While he's glad to have the charting function, Hartig said, &quot;it's not quiteas clean as the rest of the program.andP;  I hope this is just an introduction tothe charting module; I hope it comes up to the level of excellence ofIllustrator.&quot;andM;andgt;Interface.andP;  Illustrator 3.0 offers streamlined dialog boxes, tools that areeasier to identify and interactive feedback.andP;  &quot;You can select the way youwant tools to work and have more control over them,&quot; Aceves said.andP;  Hartigsaid he found the revamped interface particularly &quot;good for training andbeginners.&quot; Aceves said she liked being able to pull out guides from theruler and convert them to editable objects and being able to see a singlecontained page on-screen.andM;andgt;Other features.andP;  Adobe Separator, still bundled with the program, sports anupgraded interface and now works interactively with Illustrator documents.andO;Adobe also is bundling Version 2.0 of its $99 Adobe Type Manager softwarewith Illustrator.andM;Upgrades are $99 until Dec.andP;  31 and $149 thereafter.andP;  Users who purchasedIllustrator 88 after July 1 will receive a free upgrade.andM;Adobe Systems Inc. can be reached at 1585 Charleston Road, P.O. Box 7900,Mountain View, Calif.andP;  94039-7900; (415) 961-4400.andO;</TEXT></DOC>